## Segment 5 (40–50 min) – Designing Practical 1on1s: Preparation, Execution, Aftermath

**Purpose / intent**  
Co-create a simple checklist so participants leave with a concrete 1on1 structure they can test.

**Format**  
Whole-group co-design of a three-part checklist, mirroring the “Preparation / Execution / Aftermath” board.

**Facilitator steps**

1. Draw three headings: **Preparation**, **Execution (how to start and proceed)**, **Aftermath**.
2. Ask the group: “If we wanted our directs to put our 1on1s in the ‘Good Experience’ column, what would we do in each of these phases?” Capture 3–5 items per column, such as:
   - Preparation: fixed time on calendar, brief review of last notes, 1–2 questions tailored to the person.
   - Execution: start with their topics, ask open questions, listen more than you talk, take brief notes.
   - Aftermath: send a short summary, follow through on commitments, add next 1on1 agenda seeds.
3. Emphasize that structure is there to support **relationship power**, not to turn 1on1s into status meetings.

**Open-ended questions**

- “Which part of this checklist—preparation, execution, or aftermath—do you already do well?”
- “Where is the one small change that would most improve your directs’ experience next month?”

