## Reflection / Journaling Prompts

- “What is one specific change I will make to my 1on1s in the next two weeks, and with whom?”
- “If my directs described our 1on1s today, which items would they put in the Good vs Bad Experience columns?”
- “Where am I still tempted to treat 1on1s as status updates rather than relationship- and growth-building conversations?”

## Key Takeaways

- 1on1s are the **foundation** of the Manager Tools Trinity and the primary way managers build relationship power.
- Good 1on1s are predictable, direct-led, and focused on the person, not just tasks; bad 1on1s are cancelled, manager-dominated, and purely tactical.
- Clear structure—Preparation, Execution, Aftermath—helps 1on1s reliably provide Safety, Growth, and Fulfillment.
- Active listening in 1on1s makes later feedback easier to give and receive.

